Last week, Jordan Bernard, from Oxford Department of International Development, was given an award by the Governor of Punjab Chaudhry Mohammad Sarwar for the contribution his research has made to combat COVID-19 in Pakistan.

Speaking after receiving the award, Jordan said, 'I am overwhelmed by the response to my research. The recognition from the Governor who oversees 110 million people shows just how impactful the research has been. 

'It was an incredible honour to visit Governor House in Lahore and meet the Governor. It was a day I’ll never forget. 

'While I greatly appreciated the recognition, I’m equally overjoyed to know that the research has contributed to some extent in efforts to save lives among some of the poorest in the world. This motivates my PhD studies further.'

Congratulations, Jordan! 👏

node.text:
NEW STUDY: Oxford-led research finds that obtaining two vaccine doses remains the most effective way to ensure protection against the #COVID19 Delta variant.

Researchers analysed 2,580,021 test results from over 380,000 participants. 

Key findings from the study:

• A single dose of the Moderna vaccine has similar or greater effectiveness against the Delta variant as single doses of the other vaccines.
• Two doses of Pfizer-BioNTech have greater initial effectiveness against new COVID-19 infections, but this declines faster compared with two doses of Oxford-AstraZeneca.
• Results suggest that after four to five months effectiveness of these two vaccines would be similar – however, researchers say long-term effects need to be studied.
• The time between doses does not affect effectiveness in preventing new infections, but younger people have even more protection from vaccination than older people.

Find out more by visiting ➡️ ox.ac.uk/news/
